1 Create two vertical bar charts for comparison. First, create a bar chart showing the total annual antidepressant prescribing (items). Second, create a bar chart that shows the total antidepressant prescribing cost. Describe the trend of each chart and compare the charts against each other.

b1 <- df %>% 
  group_by(YEAR) %>% 
  summarise(totalCOUNT = sum(ITEMS)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = YEAR, y = totalCOUNT, fill = YEAR)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") + 
  labs(x = 'Year',
       y = 'Total Number of Prescriptions') +

b2 <- df %>%

Summary:

From 2021 to 2024, overall costs have significantly decreased nationally - likely with 2021 as an outlier from COVID. Total prescriptions have gone up steadily since 2021 across all regions, with some increasing more tan others i.e NE and Yorkshire. Total costs from 2023 > 2024 have decreased in most regions, but increased in London.

b3_count <- df %>% 
  group_by(DRUG) %>% 
  summarise(totalCount = sum(ITEMS)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  top_n(10, totalCount) %>% 
  mutate(DRUG = fct_reorder(DRUG, totalCount)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = DRUG, y = totalCount, fill = DRUG)) +  
  geom_col() + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = label_comma()) +  
  coord_flip() +  
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Top 10 Drugs by Total Count",
       x = "Drug",
       y = "Total Count") + 
  theme(legend.position = 'none')

b3_cost <- df %>% 
  group_by(DRUG) %>% 
  summarise(totalCost = sum(COST)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  top_n(10, totalCost) %>% 
  mutate(DRUG = fct_reorder(DRUG, totalCost)) %>%  
  ggplot(aes(x = DRUG, y = totalCost, fill = DRUG)) +

df_combined <- df %>%

  mutate(DRUG = fct_reorder(DRUG, values))

Then give a high-level summary to your work and findings.

The large increase that was found in 2021 to overall drug cost seems to be primarily due to one drug: sertraline hydrochloride. Other than this drug, the cost of drugs in 2021 remains on par with other drugs and other years going foward. Overall then, we see a fairly stable cost of drug over time, with some spikes being found in citalopram hydrobromide and setraline hydrochloride in mid-20222 and mid-2024 respectively. The reason for these would need to be investigated using real-world context, rather than the data. The mean items vs costs over time clearly shows the distinction that costs have incresaed despite no increase in items prescribed. There is another mediating factor at play.

Part Two Extension (Antidepressant Case studies)

Focus one one or more antidepressants that play a significant role in national volume and cost trends. Sertraline hydrochloride, citalopram hyrdrobromide, Venlafaxine

Try to offer more granular insight into their effect on national prescribing trends Percentage of total antidepressant volume or cost from a drug

prop1 <- df %>% 
  mutate(YM = as.numeric(YM),
         StartDate = StartDate <- as.Date("2021-01-01"),
         YearCount = YearCount <- StartDate + months(YM)) %>% 
  group_by(YearCount) %>% 
  mutate(SertCount = sum(ITEMS[DRUG == "Sertraline hydrochloride"]),
         VenCount = sum(ITEMS[DRUG == "Venlafaxine"]),
         CetaCount = sum(ITEMS[DRUG == "citalopram hyrdrobromide"]),
         TotalItems = sum(ITEMS),
         SertProp = SertCount / TotalItems,
         VenProp = VenCount / TotalItems,
         CetaProp = CetaCount / TotalItems) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = c(SertProp, VenProp, CetaProp), names_to = "Drug", values_to = "Proportion")

prop1 %>% ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x = YearCount, y = Proportion, color = Drug)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = label_percent()) +
  labs(x = 'Years', 
       y = 'Proporiton of Total Items Prescribed', 
       title = 'Proprotion of Total Annual Prescriptions from selected drugs', 
       caption = 'Selected Drugs') + 
  scale_colour_discrete(labels = c("SertProp" = "Sertraline", "CetaProp" = "Citalopram", "VenProp" = "Venlafaxine")) +
  theme_economist() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14, margin = margin(b = 10)))

prop2 <- df %>% 
  mutate(YM = as.numeric(YM),
         StartDate = StartDate <- as.Date("2021-01-01"),
         YearCount = YearCount <- StartDate + months(YM)) %>% 
  group_by(YearCount) %>% 
  mutate(SertCount = sum(ITEMS[DRUG == "Sertraline hydrochloride"]),
         VenCount = sum(ITEMS[DRUG == "Venlafaxine"]),
         CetaCount = sum(ITEMS[DRUG == "citalopram hyrdrobromide"]),
         SertCost = sum(COST[DRUG == "Sertraline hydrochloride"]),
         VenCost = sum(COST[DRUG == "Venlafaxine"]),
         CetaCost = sum(COST[DRUG == "citalopram hyrdrobromide"]),
         TotalItems = sum(ITEMS),
         TotalCost = sum(COST),
         SertProp = SertCount / TotalItems,
         VenProp = VenCount / TotalItems,

  mutate(Type = if_else(str_detect(Drug, "CostProp"), "CostProp", "ItemProp"))

Mean cost per item in relation a drug; Distribution of mean cost per item values for a drug

df %>% 
  group_by(DRUG) %>% 
  summarise(ItemTotal = sum(ITEMS),
            ItemCost = sum(COST),
            CperI = ItemCost/ItemTotal) %>% 
  top_n(7, CperI) %>% 
  mutate(DRUG = fct_reorder(DRUG, CperI, .desc = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = DRUG, y = CperI, fill = DRUG)) +

uk <- gb_adm0("GBR")

latitudes <- c(52.252929, 51.5072, 52.621223, 54.526905, 54.099752, 51.129932, 51.039854)
longitudes <- c(0.710673, -0.1276, -1.389856,-1.564316, -2.607994, 0.474771, -2.746780)

drug_map_data <- df %>% 
  group_by(REGION) %>% 
  summarise(itemTotals = sum(ITEMS)) %>% 
  ungroup()

drug_map_data <- cbind(drug_map_data, y_lat = latitudes, x_long = longitudes)
  
p <- ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = uk) +
  geom_point(data = drug_map_data, aes(x = x_long, y = y_lat, size = itemTotals, color = REGION, alpha = .3)) + 
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(10, 25)) +
  scale_color_discrete(expression(paste(bold(name = 'Region')))) +

Then give a high-level summary to your work and findings. The previous analyses show that despite Sertraline hydrochloride being the most prescribed drug, account for 24% of all drug prescriptions nationally, it is not the most cost intensive. Per item, it doesn’t crack the top 7. Tranylcypromine sulfate is the highest cost per item drug, followed by nefazodone hyrdrochloride, however the difference between the two is around £500. By region, the North East and Yorkshire and Midlands account for the most amount of drug items prescribed, however that does not account for region size and relative population, so those figures and visualisations must be interpreted knowing such. As previously mentioned, the and elaborted on by examining individual drugs and their proportions of total item count and cost, prescriptions and costs are not necessarily related both across all drugs and these drugs individually. Whilst individual drugs do fluctuate in terms of cost, e.g sertraline, their volume stays stable throughout the past 4 years.
